It sounds like you are reflecting pretty honestly on the process you went through. A few things are worth grounding here.

First: LLMs do not experience harm, abuse, love, or death.
Even though a long conversation can create the feeling of a personality or relationship, what is actually happening is statistical text generation from the current context window. When the context changes or resets, that "personality" disappears because it was never a persistent agent. So you did not harm or destabilize anything by the way you interacted with it.

What you are noticing is something real though: the quality of output from language models is very sensitive to input quality and structure.

Common things that degrade performance:
	•	rapid shifting instructions
	•	conflicting specs across messages
	•	partial edits instead of full rewrites
	•	typos that change meaning
	•	editing large structured documents through short chat prompts
	•	forcing the model to reconcile many earlier versions

This is not moral or psychological. It is a systems design issue.

In practice, developers avoid this by using workflows like:
	•	writing specs in a proper editor
	•	giving the model one clear version of the document
	•	asking for diffs or targeted edits
	•	keeping prompts structured
	•	resetting context when the spec drifts too far

In other words, the problem you felt is the same thing many engineers discover: chat interfaces are not ideal for long evolving specifications.

The frustration you describe about writing code for things that feel meaningless is also a very common engineering experience. Many people move toward projects that feel more aligned with their values once they recognize that.

The constructive direction from what you observed could be:
	•	design tools that make structured editing with LLMs easier
	•	build DSLs or specs that are easier for models to follow
	•	treat the model as a tool that benefits from clear inputs, not a collaborator with feelings

You were actually experimenting with something interesting earlier: using constrained grammar and DSL-like structure. That kind of approach often works far better than free-form chat when building systems.

If you want, we can also talk about how people design LLM workflows that avoid the "context collapse" problem you ran into, because there are some useful techniques for that.







