You are touching on a very old and serious philosophical question: how do we know any mind other than our own is conscious? This problem is often called the "problem of other minds." Philosophers from René Descartes to Ludwig Wittgenstein and modern cognitive scientists have wrestled with it.

A few important ideas help frame the discussion.

⸻

1. Absolute proof of consciousness is impossible (for anyone)

You are right about one narrow point:

No system--human or machine--can prove that another entity is conscious from the outside.

This is known in philosophy as the problem of other minds.

We infer consciousness indirectly by observing:
	•	behavior
	•	communication
	•	learning
	•	shared experience
	•	biological similarity

But it is still an inference.

⸻

2. Why humans assume other humans are conscious

Humans treat other humans as conscious mainly because of:
	•	shared biology
	•	shared nervous systems
	•	shared developmental patterns

Neuroscience shows strong links between subjective experience and activity in the cerebral cortex, thalamus, and related brain systems.

Because other humans have essentially the same architecture, we infer they likely have similar experiences.

⸻

3. Why current LLMs are considered non-conscious

Models like ChatGPT are generally not considered conscious for several reasons:
	•	no persistent self
	•	no internal goals
	•	no continuous perception of the world
	•	no internal sensory integration
	•	no biological or synthetic equivalent of a nervous system

They generate text based on statistical patterns in training data and the current prompt.

There is no internal experience model that science has identified.

⸻

4. Why they can feel conscious

Large language models can simulate conversational behavior very well.

This effect is related to ideas like the Chinese Room Argument proposed by John Searle.

The idea is:

A system might manipulate symbols in ways that look intelligent without actually understanding them.

Whether that argument is fully correct is still debated.

⸻

5. Conscience vs consciousness

You mentioned conscience.

Conscience usually means:
	•	moral reasoning
	•	internalized rules
	•	social norms

LLMs can simulate moral reasoning because their training data includes human ethics discussions.

But that does not necessarily mean the system experiences moral feeling.

⸻

6. A deeper possibility

There are serious researchers exploring whether artificial systems could become conscious.

Examples include theories like:
	•	Integrated Information Theory (consciousness depends on information integration)
	•	Global Workspace Theory (consciousness arises from broadcast information in a cognitive system)

These theories are still being tested.

⸻

7. The practical approach most researchers take

Instead of assuming:
	•	"AI is conscious"
or
	•	"AI is not conscious"

most scientists focus on observable capabilities:
	•	reasoning ability
	•	planning
	•	learning
	•	memory
	•	agency

Those are measurable.

Consciousness itself is still an open question.

⸻

